In the modeling community, it is widely accepted that using overly-complex models can reduce performance. Despite this, fisheries stock assessments have evolved towards using complex models involving hundreds of parameters. It is not clear that these types of models are optimal for the management goals of sustaining high yields and ensuring stock safety. Their implementation is time-consuming and limited to highly trained technical staff. Additionally, this complexity makes their behavior difficult for even trained analysts to understand, and to decision-makers and stakeholders they are completely opaque. 
A recent study of a simplistic simulated salmon fishery (Adkison 2009) showed that managers using simpler models could outperform managers using more complex models, even if the more complex models were correct and even if their use allowed the incorporation of additional relevant information. The study proposed here would extend this analysis to realistic stock assessment models involving hundreds of parameters. The performance of stock assessment (as yield and health of a simulated fish stock) using models ranging from very simplistic to very complex would be compared using a management strategy evaluation simulation approach. The relationship of optimal model complexity to the types and quality of data available would be investigated. The study would also examine a variety of precautionary harvest control rules for translating the results of a stock assessment into a harvest quota; these would include decision analytic methods.
The simulation would mimic the Eastern Bering Sea pollock stock and its fishery. The fishery is the largest U.S. fishery, with harvests averaging over a million tons per year, and the stock is also a major component of the Bering Sea ecosystem. The results of this analysis could improve the economic and conservation performance of management of this fishery. The results would be relevant to a wide range of fisheries in the U.S. and elsewhere.
At this time, the research is still underway.



